-- в•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җв•җ
-- Ready set: { handle-cycle, sub-analyzer-mayor, ... }
-- Pick: handle-cycle

вҠў handle-cycle
  given validate-acyclicityвҶ’is-acyclic вүЎ false   -- guard: is-acyclic = false вҶ’ TRUE вң“
  given validate-acyclicityвҶ’cycle-description вүЎ "Two overlapping cycles detected. Cycle 1: gt вҶ’ mayor вҶ’ gt. Cycle 2: gt вҶ’ witness вҶ’ mayor вҶ’ gt."
  yield dag-status, cycle-analysis

-- LLM evaluation:

  yield dag-status вүЎ "cyclic"

  yield cycle-analysis вүЎ "The cycles all involve gt as the hub. The fundamental issue: gt is BOTH an orchestration layer (invoked BY agents) AND a dependency of agents (agents call gt commands). This is an architectural smell вҖ” the CLI tool and the agent coordination logic are conflated. To break the cycle: separate gt into two layers. (1) gt-cli: the pure CLI tool that translates human/agent commands into API calls. This has NO internal dependencies вҖ” it's a thin wrapper. (2) gt-core: the coordination logic (dispatch, escalate, nudge) that depends on beads, dolt, and the individual agent modules. Agents would depend on gt-cli (for command invocation) but NOT on gt-core. gt-core would depend on agents (for dispatch). The one-way dependency: agents вҶ’ gt-cli вҶ’ nothing; gt-core вҶ’ agents вҶ’ gt-cli. This breaks both cycles. Alternative: treat gt as pure infrastructure (like dolt) and invert the dependency вҖ” agents don't 'depend on' gt, they are 'invoked by' gt. Under this framing, the graph becomes: gt вҶ’ {mayor, witness, refinery} вҶ’ beads вҶ’ dolt, which is acyclic."

-- oracle checks:
--   вҠЁ dag-status = "cyclic" вҶ’ вң“
--   вҠЁ cycle-analysis proposes at least one way to break the cycle вҶ’ вң“
--     (Two proposals: split gt into gt-cli/gt-core; or invert to treat gt as infrastructure)

